": 30, "text": "A developer&#x27;s machine accumulates tools fast. A Rust CLI you compiled last year, a Python formatter installed via `uv`, a language server pulled from npm, a terminal emulator from a curl script, a Go binary built from source. Each came from a different package manager, each with its own install incantation you half-remember.<p>I wanted a way to declare what I need without adopting a complex system like Nix or Ansible just for a single laptop. The result was a plain old Makefile.<p>I wrote a short post on using Make (along with a tiny bash script and fzf) to create a searchable, single-command registry for all your local dev tools. It\u2019s not a new framework or a heavy tool\u2014just a simple way to organize the package managers we already use.<p>If you&#x27;re tired of losing track of your local environment, you might find it useful.", "fetched_at": "2026-04-03T14:22:58.086152", "published_at": "2026-03-29T06:56:04"}]